Testing Number of People Per Room - Bin Cutoffs

Note for user regarding this R Notebook:

This notebook explains our decision regarding the variable “number of people per room.” Because this variable had a disproportionate number of levels compared to the other variables included in the MCA models, we binned the ranges 0-2 people per room, 3-9 people per room, and 10+ people per room, yielding three levels from more nearly 20. We found that both binning the variable and varying the bin cutoffs had little effect on the household wealth scores. In this section, we demonstrate these changes’ effects with Indices 1 & 2.

In order to knit the document fully, we must first include the code to build indices 1 & 2 (including loading and subsetting the data, re-leveling the variables, and building the MCA models), as the comparison plots reference the values generated by the MCA models. These pieces of code will make the notebook longer to knit, but will not appear in the output file.

Comparing number.ppl.per.room.1 binned (as in Index 1) vs unbinned (as pulled from IPUMS-I)

Building the MCA models using “number of people per room” as read from IPUMS-I (Index 1, 2 unbinned):

country_1.sub.unbinned = select(country_1, c(ownership.1, 
                                      electric.1, 
                                      water.supply.1, 
                                      sewage.simple.1, 
                                      #sewage.detailed.1,
                                      cooking.fuel.1,
                                      trash.1,
                                      #heat.1,
                                      #aircon.1,
                                      number.ppl.per.room.1,
                                      toilet.1,
                                      floor.1,
                                      wall.1,
                                      roof.1))

country_2.sub.unbinned = select(country_2, c(ownership.1, 
                                      electric.1, 
                                      water.supply.1, 
                                      sewage.general.1,
                                      cooking.fuel.1,
                                      number.ppl.per.room.1,
                                      toilet.1,
                                      dwelling.1))

country_1.mca.unbinned = MCA(country_1.sub.unbinned,row.w = country_1$Household.weight, graph = FALSE)
country_2.mca.unbinned = MCA(country_2.sub.unbinned,row.w = country_2$Household.weight, graph = FALSE)
